<h2 dir="ltr"><span>FAQs&nbsp;</span></h2>
<p dir="ltr"><h4>1. What is BMI and why is it important?</h4><span></span><span>BMI (Body Mass Index) is a number calculated using your height and weight. It helps check if you’re underweight, healthy, overweight, or obese. This is a quick insight into your overall health risks.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><h4>2. Is BMI a reliable measure of health?</h4><span></span><span> BMI is a useful tool, but it is not a complete health indicator. It doesn’t consider muscle mass, bone density, or fat distribution, so it’s best used with other health markers to know the complete picture.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><h4>3. Can I have a normal BMI and still be unhealthy?</h4><span></span><span> Yes, a normal BMI doesn’t always mean you’re healthy. Lifestyle habits like diet, physical activity, and stress are the factors that play a major role in your actual well-being.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><h4>4. What should I do if my BMI is too high or low?</h4><span></span><span>First of all, you need to know that it’s perfectly fine if you are in the ideal range of BMI. Don’t panic! Start by focusing on balanced nutrition, regular exercise, and proper sleep. Small, consistent changes can bring long-term results. If it is required, consider consulting with a healthcare specialist.</span></p>
<p dir="ltr"><h4>5. Does age or gender affect BMI results?</h4><span></span><span>BMI is calculated the same way for adults regardless of age or gender. These factors do not affect the results but other factors like muscle mass and hormonal changes can impact how BMI reflects your body’s actual composition. That is why we don’t fully rely on BMI.&nbsp;</span></p>
